You are relying on database session settings here. Is &#39;09/02/2019&#39; February 2 or September 9? Does the setting allow &#39;/&#39; to be a date part separator? Better use an unambiguous format. That is `&#39;YYYYMMDD&#39;`  for all SQL Server versions (or `&#39;YYYY-MM-DD&#39;` for newer ones).

Then, what type are your date columns? If they are datetimes actually, there may be time parts you don&#39;t see. You can cast to date to play safe.

    DECLARE @StartDate DateTime = &#39;2019-09-02&#39;
    DECLARE @EndDate DateTime = &#39;2019-09-20&#39;
    
    SELECT * 
    FROM MyTable
    WHERE (@StartDate BETWEEN CAST(DateFrom AS DATE) AND CAST(DateTo AS DATE)) 
       OR (@EndDate BETWEEN CAST(DateFrom AS DATE) AND CAST(DateTo AS DATE));

Since date formats can be different on each machine, I suggest you to use `DATEFROMPARTS(year, month, day)` instead of a literal string. 

Use it like this:


    DECLARE @StartDate DateTime = DATEFROMPARTS(2019, 2, 9) ;
    DECLARE @EndDate DateTime = DATEFROMPARTS(2019, 9, 20) ;

